    {
      "id": "vowel-pairs",
      "title": "2. Hard vs. soft vowels",
      "summary": "Russian vowels come in pairs that signal whether the preceding consonant is hard or soft — the backbone of Russian pronunciation and spelling.",
      "summary_ar": "تأتي حروف العلة الروسية في أزواج تدلّ على ما إذا كان الحرف الساكن السابق مُفخَّمًا (صلبًا) أو مُرقَّقًا (ليّنًا) — وهي العمود الفقري للنطق والإملاء في الروسية.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "prose",
          "html": "Each of Russia's vowel sounds has two letters: one marks a preceding <strong>hard</strong> consonant, the other a <strong>soft</strong> (palatalised) one. At the start of a word or after a vowel, the soft-series letters add a /j/ (\"y\") glide."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "caption": "The five vowel pairs",
          "headers": [
            "Hard",
            "Soft",
            "Sound after consonant",
            "Initial / after vowel"
          ],
          "rows": [
