    {
      "id": "stress-reduction",
      "title": "3. Stress & vowel reduction",
      "summary": "Russian stress is free and mobile, and unstressed vowels reduce. This single rule explains most of the gap between spelling and speech.",
      "summary_ar": "النبر في الروسية حُرّ ومتنقّل، وحروف العلة غير المنبورة تُختزَل. وهذه القاعدة الواحدة تفسّر معظم الفجوة بين الكتابة والنطق.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "prose",
          "html": "Every Russian word has exactly one <strong>stressed</strong> syllable, pronounced longer and clearer. Stress is <em>free</em> (it can fall anywhere) and <em>mobile</em> (it can move between forms of the same word: <strong>рука́</strong> → <strong>ру́ки</strong>). Dictionaries mark it with an acute accent; ordinary text does not."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Unstressed <strong>О</strong> is pronounced like /a/: молоко́ sounds like 'malako'.",
            "Unstressed <strong>Е</strong> and <strong>Я</strong> reduce toward /i/: язы́к sounds like 'yizyk'.",
            "Getting stress wrong is the #1 marker of a foreign accent — learn each word's stress with the word itself."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "examples",
          "items": [
            {
              "ru": "молоко́",
              "tr": "məlakó",
              "en": "milk — first two О's reduce",
              "ar": "حليب — حرفا О الأوّلان يُختزَلان",
              "ku": "شیر — دوو پیتی О ی یەکەم کورت دەکرێنەوە"
            },
            {
              "ru": "хорошо́",
              "tr": "xərašó",
              "en": "good/well — only the last О is full",
              "ar": "جيّد/حَسَنًا — حرف О الأخير وحده كامل النطق",
              "ku": "باش/چاک — تەنها پیتی О ی کۆتایی بە تەواوی دەردەبڕدرێت"
            },
            {
              "ru": "за́мок / замо́к",
              "tr": "zámak / zamók",
              "en": "castle vs. lock — stress changes meaning",
              "ar": "قَلعة مقابل قُفل — موضع النبر يُغيّر المعنى",
              "ku": "قەڵا بەرامبەر قوفڵ — جێی فشار واتاکە دەگۆڕێت"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "consonant-rules",
      "title": "4. Consonant assimilation & devoicing",
      "summary": "Voiced consonants devoice at the end of words and assimilate to their neighbours.",
      "summary_ar": "الحروف الساكنة المجهورة تُصبح مهموسة في نهاية الكلمات وتتماثل مع الحروف المجاورة لها.",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "<strong>Final devoicing:</strong> voiced consonants become voiceless at the end of a word — хле<strong>б</strong> sounds like 'khlep', горо<strong>д</strong> like 'gorot'.",
            "<strong>Regressive assimilation:</strong> a consonant takes the voicing of the one after it — во<strong>дк</strong>а sounds like 'votka', <strong>сд</strong>елать like 'zdelat'.",
            "<strong>Spelling stays constant</strong> even though the sound changes — this is why reading aloud needs the rules above."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "html": "Voiced/voiceless pairs: Б/П, В/Ф, Г/К, Д/Т, Ж/Ш, З/С. Always voiceless: Х, Ц, Ч, Щ. Always voiced (sonorant): Л, М, Н, Р, Й."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
